06663nam a22007695i 9780773554184DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20182018xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735541847 a10.1515/97807735541842doi  a(DE-B1597)657925  a(OCoLC)1035218240  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aJL198b.P83 2018 7aPOL0560002bisacsh04a336/.0137122304aThe Public Sector in an Age of Austerity :bPerspectives from Canada’s Provinces and Territories /ced. by Bryan M. Evans, Carlo Fanelli. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource :b21 tables, 33 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tThe Permanent Unequal Union: Canada's Provinces and Territories in an Era of Neoliberalism -- tBC's Recurrent Austerity: Victory Unfettered from Success -- tAlberta and the Great Recession: Neoliberalism, Conservative Government, and Public Finance -- tActive Incrementalism and the Politics of Austerity in the “New Saskatchewan” -- tManitoba: Fiscal Policy and the Public Sector under “Today's NDP” -- tOntario in an Age of Austerity: Common Sense Reloaded -- tFrom the Bailiffs at Our Doors to the Greek Peril: Twenty Years of Fiscal “Urgency” and Quebec Politics -- tBetween “The Rock” and a Hard Place: Fiscal Policy in New Brunswick since 2007 -- tProvincial Fiscal Strategies and Public-Sector Management in Nova Scotia -- tAusterity in the Garden Province of Prince Edward Island -- tNewfoundland's Boom: A Study in the Political Culture of Neoliberalism -- tNunavut: Conceived in Austerity -- tFiscally Conservative Governance without Austerity: Devolution, Aboriginal Self-Government, and the Northwest Territories -- tFiscal Outlier: Yukon in an Austere Age -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFollowing the 2008 global financial crisis, Canada appeared to escape the austerity implemented elsewhere, but this was spin hiding the reality. A closer look reveals that the provinces – responsible for delivering essential public and social services such as education and healthcare – shouldered the burden. The Public Sector in an Age of Austerity examines public-sector austerity in the provinces and territories, specifically addressing how austerity was implemented, what forms austerity agendas took (from regressive taxes and new user fees to public-sector layoffs and privatization schemes), and what, if any, political responses resulted. Contributors focus on the period from 2007 to 2015, the global financial crisis and the period of fiscal consolidation that followed, while also providing a longer historical context – austerity is not a new phenomenon. A granular examination of each jurisdiction identifies how changing fiscal conditions have affected the delivery of public services and restructured public finances, highlighting the consequences such changes have had for public-sector workers and users of public services. The first book of its kind in Canada, The Public Sector in an Age of Austerity challenges conventional wisdom by showing that Canada did not escape post-crisis austerity, and that its recovery has been vastly overstated.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCivil servicezCanadaxProvinces. 0aFinance, PubliczCanadaxProvinces. 0aFiscal policyzCanadaxProvinces. 0aGlobal Financial Crisis, 2008-2009xGovernment policyzCanadaxProvinces. 0aNeoliberalismzCanadaxProvinces. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aBrownsey, Keith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCamfield, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca